<subSubSection pageId="14" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph blockId="14.[151,1436,1305,2017]" pageId="14">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[151,266,1305,1330]" pageId="14">Diagnosis</emphasis>
: Head and thorax covered in conspicuous hairs (
<figureCitation box="[820,908,1305,1330]" captionStart="FIGURES 10 – 27" captionStartId="7.[151,264,1910,1933]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,195,1873]" captionTargetId="figure@7.[151,1436,195,1889]" captionTargetPageId="7" captionText="FIGURES 10 – 27. Head, anterodorsal view. 10. Gyropsylla sp. 11. Lanthanaphalara sp. 12. Limataphalara hollisi. 13. Ctenarytaina spatulata. 14. Glycaspis brimblecombei. 15. Syncoptozus mexicanus. 16. Paracarsidara sp. 17. Synoza cornutiventris. 18. Caradocia sp. 19. Diaphorina citri. 20. Katacephala sp. 21. Tuthillia latipennis. 22 – 23. Calophya schini. 24 – 25. Mastigimas sp. 26. Acizzia uncatoides. 27. Ciriacremum sp." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/1059237/files/figure.png" pageId="14">Figs 21</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation box="[921,953,1305,1330]" captionStart="FIGURES 59 – 70" captionStartId="16.[151,264,1559,1582]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,409,1539]" captionTargetId="figure@16.[151,1436,409,1539]" captionTargetPageId="16" captionText="FIGURES 59 – 70. Habitus, lateral view. 59. Limataphalara hollisi. 60. Syncoptozus mexicanus. 61. Paracarsidara sp. 62. Synoza cornutiventris. 63. Diaphorina citri. 64. Tuthillia latipennis. 65. Mastigimas sp. 66. Ciriacremum sp. 67. Euceropsylla sp. 68. Calinda sp. 69. Leuronota sp. 70. Triozoida sp." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/1059245/files/figure.png" pageId="14">64</figureCitation>
). Head as broad as or broader than thorax; vertex rectangular to trapezoidal; genal processes with the outer margin straight and the inner strongly convex from above; occipital sclerite may be developed as a tubercle; lateral ocelli raised on tubercles close to posterior margin of eye; anteorbital tubercles present (
<figureCitation box="[571,656,1413,1438]" captionStart="FIGURES 10 – 27" captionStartId="7.[151,264,1910,1933]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,195,1873]" captionTargetId="figure@7.[151,1436,195,1889]" captionTargetPageId="7" captionText="FIGURES 10 – 27. Head, anterodorsal view. 10. Gyropsylla sp. 11. Lanthanaphalara sp. 12. Limataphalara hollisi. 13. Ctenarytaina spatulata. 14. Glycaspis brimblecombei. 15. Syncoptozus mexicanus. 16. Paracarsidara sp. 17. Synoza cornutiventris. 18. Caradocia sp. 19. Diaphorina citri. 20. Katacephala sp. 21. Tuthillia latipennis. 22 – 23. Calophya schini. 24 – 25. Mastigimas sp. 26. Acizzia uncatoides. 27. Ciriacremum sp." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/1059237/files/figure.png" pageId="14">Fig. 21</figureCitation>
). Antenna 1.2–2.2 times the head width; segments 9 and 10 broader; setae on antennae longer than width of segments; segment 3 the longest; segment 10 longer than 9. Forewing somewhat rectangular, broad to very elongate; veins bearing prominent setae much longer than the diameter of veins; Rs long and sinuous; vein M1+2 strongly arched upwards; rs-m crossvein occasionally present; C+Sc and pterostigma somewhat thickened; costal break present. Meracanthus prominent; metatibia without genual spine and with a crown of 8–14 apical spurs; metabasitarsus with 2 apical spurs. Male proctiger densely hairy with broad posterior lobes.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection lastPageId="15" pageId="14" type="biology_ecology">
<paragraph blockId="14.[151,1436,1305,2017]" pageId="14">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,477,1668,1693]" pageId="14">Biology and damages:</emphasis>
<taxonomicName authority="Hodkinson, Brown &amp; Burckhardt" authorityName="Hodkinson, Brown &amp; Burckhardt" authorityYear="1986" box="[492,1104,1668,1693]" class="Insecta" family="Liviidae" genus="Tuthillia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="14" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="cognata">
<emphasis box="[492,692,1668,1693]" italics="true" pageId="14">Tuthillia cognata</emphasis>
Hodkinson, Brown &amp; Burckhardt
</taxonomicName>
represents a major pest in plantations of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="McVaugh (Kunth" authorityYear="1963" box="[317,504,1704,1729]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Myrtaceae" genus="Myrciaria" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" order="Myrtales" pageId="14" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="dubia">
<emphasis box="[317,504,1704,1729]" italics="true" pageId="14">Myrciaria dubia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, also known as camu-camu (
<bibRefCitation author="Couturier" box="[844,1094,1704,1729]" pageId="14" refString="Couturier, G., Inga Sanchez, H. &amp; Tanchiva Flores, E. (1992) Insectos fitofagos que viven en Myrciaria dubia (Myrtaceae), frutal amazonico en la region de Loreto - Peru. Folia Amazonica, 4 (1), 19 - 29." type="journal article" year="1992">
Couturier 
<emphasis box="[964,1023,1704,1729]" italics="true" pageId="14">et al.</emphasis>
1992
</bibRefCitation>
). Damage includes curling of apical leaves which turn yellow and wither (
<bibRefCitation author="Burckhardt" box="[643,979,1740,1765]" pageId="14" refString="Burckhardt, D. &amp; Couturier, G. (1988) Biology and taxonomy of Tuthillia cognata (Homoptera: Psylloidea), a pest on Myrciaria dubia (Myrtaceae). Annales de la Societe Entomologique de France, Nouvelle Serie, 24 (3), 257 - 261." type="journal article" year="1988">Burckhardt &amp; Couturier 1988</bibRefCitation>
), dessication of buds and terminal leaves preventing plant growth (
<bibRefCitation author="Couturier" box="[434,672,1776,1801]" pageId="14" refString="Couturier, G., Inga Sanchez, H. &amp; Tanchiva Flores, E. (1992) Insectos fitofagos que viven en Myrciaria dubia (Myrtaceae), frutal amazonico en la region de Loreto - Peru. Folia Amazonica, 4 (1), 19 - 29." type="journal article" year="1992">
Couturier 
<emphasis box="[550,606,1776,1801]" italics="true" pageId="14">et al.</emphasis>
1992
</bibRefCitation>
); immatures are found inside the leaf-curls producing great amounts of waxy secretions (
<bibRefCitation author="Burckhardt" box="[373,709,1812,1837]" pageId="14" refString="Burckhardt, D. &amp; Couturier, G. (1988) Biology and taxonomy of Tuthillia cognata (Homoptera: Psylloidea), a pest on Myrciaria dubia (Myrtaceae). Annales de la Societe Entomologique de France, Nouvelle Serie, 24 (3), 257 - 261." type="journal article" year="1988">Burckhardt &amp; Couturier 1988</bibRefCitation>
). 
<taxonomicName authority="Burckhardt, Queiroz, Marsaro Junior &amp; Wyniger" authorityName="Burckhardt, Queiroz, Marsaro Junior &amp; Wyniger" box="[728,1436,1812,1837]" class="Insecta" family="Liviidae" genus="Tuthillia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="14" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="myrcianthis">
<emphasis box="[728,886,1812,1837]" italics="true" pageId="14">T. myrcianthis</emphasis>
Burckhardt, Queiroz, Marsaro Junior &amp; Wyniger
</taxonomicName>
induces irregular blister galls on the adaxial surface of fresh leaves of 
<taxonomicName box="[984,1227,1848,1873]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Myrtaceae" genus="Myrcianthes" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" order="Myrtales" pageId="14" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="pungens">
<emphasis box="[984,1227,1848,1873]" italics="true" pageId="14">Myrcianthes pungens</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. Inside the gall a colony of immatures develops which are covered in long threads of wax (Burckhardt 
<emphasis box="[1134,1192,1884,1909]" italics="true" pageId="14">et al.</emphasis>
2012). Specimens of 
<taxonomicName authority="Hodkinson, Brown &amp; Burckhardt" authorityName="Hodkinson, Brown &amp; Burckhardt" authorityYear="1986" box="[151,745,1920,1945]" class="Insecta" family="Liviidae" genus="Tuthillia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="14" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="latipennis">
<emphasis box="[151,363,1920,1945]" italics="true" pageId="14">Tuthillia latipennis</emphasis>
Hodkinson, Brown &amp; Burckhardt
</taxonomicName>
were collected in 
<collectingCountry box="[950,1060,1920,1945]" name="Colombia" pageId="14">Colombia</collectingCountry>
on 
<taxonomicName authorityName="O.C. Berg" authorityYear="1856" box="[1102,1241,1920,1945]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Myrtaceae" genus="Myrcianthes" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" order="Myrtales" pageId="14" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[1102,1241,1920,1945]" italics="true" pageId="14">Myrcianthes</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
sp. whose leaves presented deformations as shown in 
<figureCitation box="[578,664,1956,1981]" captionStart="FIGURES 71 – 76. 71" captionStartId="19.[151,264,785,808]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,206,765]" captionTargetId="figure@19.[151,1436,193,765]" captionTargetPageId="19" captionText="FIGURES 71 – 76. 71. Pit-galls of Calophya schini on Schinus molle. 72 – 73. Mastigimas cedrelae on Cedrela montana. 74. Tuthillia latipennis on Myrcianthes sp. 75 – 76. Acizzia uncatoides on Acacia sp." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/1059247/files/figure.png" pageId="14">Fig. 74</figureCitation>
; immatures were found in groups confined to those deformations, covered with threads of wax (field observation).
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="15.[151,1436,151,392]" box="[199,1239,151,176]" pageId="15">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,347,151,176]" pageId="15">Host-plants:</emphasis>
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Hodkinson" baseAuthorityYear="1989" box="[354,472,152,176]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Myrtaceae" kingdom="Plantae" order="Myrtales" pageId="15" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="family">Myrtaceae</taxonomicName>
(Burckhardt &amp; Queiroz 2012; Burckhardt 
<emphasis box="[951,1007,151,176]" italics="true" pageId="15">et al.</emphasis>
2012; NHMB data).
</paragraph>
